message.content:
This command establishes a secure SSH tunnel to an EC2 instance located in the US West (Oregon) region. Here's a breakdown:

* **ssh:** The command used for Secure Shell connections.

* **-i "~/UserKey.pem":** Specifies the path to your private key file used for authentication. 

* **-C:** Enables compression of the SSH connection, improving performance.
* **-L 25900:localhost:5900:** This is the crucial part - it sets up a local port forwarding.  Traffic on port 25900 on your local machine will be forwarded to port 5900 of the remote EC2 instance.

* **user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com:** This is the username and hostname (public IP address) of the target EC2 instance.


**In essence, this command allows you to access a service running on port 5900 of the EC2 instance from your local machine by connecting to port 25900.**

A common use case for this type of tunnel is accessing graphical applications or remote desktops that are running on the EC2 instance.
